                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.60 p 31/11: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Latvia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">White</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Riga</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-10-25T12:00:00+01:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 25, 1924—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received 12:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>166. Discussed with Foreign Minister Seya the desirability of proceeding with
                    temporary most-favored-nation agreement. As he considers that there is no
                    prospect of new maximum and minimum tariff taking effect before next spring, he
                    is in favor of waiting for regular commercial treaty. He has assured me,
                    however, that the maximum tariff will not be applied against the United States,
                    and in order to prevent such a contingency the Government of Latvia would
                    unquestionably sign a temporary agreement when actual necessity arose.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">White</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
